03962nam a22005415i 9780228006435DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280064357 a10.1515/97802280064352doi  a(DE-B1597)657954  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLC3536.S34bK67 2021 7aSOC0620002bisacsh04a371.829/94570482231 aKortekangas, Otso, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLanguage, Citizenship, and Sámi Education in the Nordic North, 1900-1940 /cOtso Kortekangas. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b10 photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTable and Figures -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Sámi Language in Sámi Lands? -- tThe Sámi: Historical Background -- tSweden -- tFinland -- tNorway -- tLanguage, Citizenship, and Sámi Education in the Nordic North, 1900–1940 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the making of the modern Nordic states in the first half of the twentieth century, elementary education was paramount in creating a notion of citizenship that was universal and equal for all citizens. Yet these elementary education policies ignored, in most cases, the language, culture, wishes, and needs of minorities such as the indigenous Sámi.Presenting the Sámi as an active, transnational population in early twentieth-century northern Europe, Otso Kortekangas examines how educational policies affected the Sámi people residing in the northern parts of Norway, Sweden, and Finland. In this detailed study, Kortekangas explores what the arguments were for the lack of Sámi language in schools, how Sámi teachers have promoted the use of their mother tongue within the school systems, and how the history of the Sámi compares to other indigenous and minority populations globally.Timely in its focus on educational policies in multiethnic societies, and ambitious in its scope, the book provides essential information for educators, policy-makers, and academics, as well as anyone interested in the history of education, and the relationship between large-scale government policies and indigenous peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation and statezScandinaviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLanguage and culturezScandinaviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLanguage and educationzScandinaviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSami (European people)xEducationxGovernment policyzScandinaviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSami (European people)xEducationzScandinaviaxHistoryy20thcentury. 0aSami languagexStudy and teachingzScandinaviaxHistoryy20thcentury. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aStenbaek, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228006435?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228006435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228006435/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles